":"1250","August 1258":"srpen 1258","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","ABT 1250":"okolo 1250","1258":"1258","1247":"1247","1167":"1167","1254":"1254","about 1254":"okolo 1254","1308":"1308","Badenoch, Inverness-Shire, Scotland":"Badenoch, Inverness-shire, Scotland","Buchan, Aberdeen, Scotland":"Buchan, Aberdeenshire, Skotsko, United Kingdom","Buchan, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Buchan, Aberdeenshire, Skotsko, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Forres, Morayshire, Scotland":"Forres, Elginshire, Scotland"},"da":{"about 1160–1258":"omkring 1160–1258","1167–1254":"1167–1254","1180–1258":"1180–1258","1247–Female":"1247–Afdød","1250–1308":"1250–1308","1160–1258":"1160–1258","about 1160":"omkring 1160","Abt 1247":"omkring 1247","1250":"1250","August 1258":"august 1258","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","ABT 1250":"omkring 1250","1258":"1258","1247":"1247","1167":"1167","1254":"1254","about 1254":"omkring 1254","1308":"1308","Badenoch, Inverness-Shire, Scotland":"Badenoch, Inverness-shire, Skotland","Buchan, Aberdeen, Scotland":"Buchan, Aberdeenshire, Skotland, United Kingdom","Buchan, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Buchan, Aberdeenshire, Skotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Skotland","Forres, Morayshire, Scotland":"Forres, Elginshire, Skotland"},"nl":{"about 1160–1258":"circa 1160–1258","1167–1254":"1167–1254","1180–1258":"1180–1258","1247–Female":"1247–Overleden","1250–1308":"1250–1308","1160–1258":"1160–1258","about 1160":"circa 1160","Abt 1247":"circa 1247","1250":"1250","August 1258":"augustus 1258","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","ABT 1250":"circa 1250","1258":"1258","1247":"1247","1167":"1167","1254":"1254","about 1254":"circa 1254","1308":"1308","Badenoch, Inverness-Shire, Scotland":"Badenoch, Inverness-shire, Schotland","Buchan, Aberdeen, Scotland":"Buchan, Aberdeenshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Buchan, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Buchan, Aberdeenshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Scotland":"Schotland","Forres, Morayshire, Scotland":"Forres, Elginshire, Schotland"},"en":{"about 1160–1258":"about 1160–1258","1167–1254":"1167–1254","1180–1258":"1180–1258","1247–Female":"1247–Deceased","1250–1308":"1250–1308","1160–1258":"1160–1258","about 1160":"about 1160","Abt 1247":"about 1247","1250":"1250","August 1258":"August 1258","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","ABT 1250":"about 1250","1258":"1258","1247":"1247","1167":"1167","1254":"1254","about 1254":"about 1254","1308":"1308","Badenoch, Inverness-Shire, Scotland":"Badenoch, Inverness-shire, Scotland","Buchan, Aberdeen, Scotland":"Buchan, Aberdeenshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Buchan, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Buchan, Aberdeenshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Forres, Morayshire, Scotland":"Forres, Elginshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Comyn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English, Irish:  see  Cumming  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cumming","meanings":["Scottish (of Norman origin): most probably a habitational name from Bosc-Benard-Commin in Eure, France. This place lies on the edge of the Forêt de Rouvray, near Rouen, in the heart of the district from which came numerous Domesday barons, and so is much more likely to be the source of the name than Comines in Nord. The name is also possibly derived from the personal name <i>Cumin</i>, which is found in Norfolk, Lincolnshire, and Yorkshire in the 12th and 13th centuries and may be of Breton origin, according to Reaney. Compare Old Breton <i>Cunmin</i>, which also appears as <i>Cumin</i>, and is from <i>con-</i> ‘hound’ with an uncertain second element, perhaps the <i>min</i> ‘edge’ which is found in other personal names.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Cuimín</b> (or <b>Ó Cuimín</b>) ‘son (or ‘descendant’) of <i>Cuimín</i>’, a personal name formed from a diminutive of <i>cam</i> ‘crooked’. There was a 7th-century abbot of Iona named <i>Cumin</i>. In Scotland, this Irish surname became confused with the Norman name.","History: A notable bearer of the Norman surname is Wilhelmus Comyn, Bishop of Durham, who came north to Scotland with King David I in 1124 and was appointed Chancellor of Scotland. He established his nephew Richard in Tynedale and Roxburghshire, and Richard also rose to be Chancellor of Scotland. The Comyn or Cumming family gained the earldoms of Buchan and Menteith and rose to be the most powerful noble family in Scotland in the century before the rise of King Robert Bruce."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]},{"name":"or","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally the name of the god of thunder in Norse mythology, Thor (Old Norse <i>Þórr</i>). It was not used as a personal name during the Middle Ages. The modern name is either a late 18th-century revival of the god's name or else a vernacular development of   Tord ."],"variants":[{"name":"Thor","meanings":["Originally the name of the god of thunder in Norse mythology, Thor (Old Norse <i>Þórr</i>). It was not used as a personal name during the Middle Ages. The modern name is either a late 18th-century revival of the god's name or else a vernacular development of   Tord ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Walter or William Comyn was born about 1160, in Forres, Elginshire, Scotland. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Sarah FitzHugh. He died in 1258, in Scotland, at the age of 99."},"et":{"about 1160–1258":"umbes 1160–1258","1167–1254":"1167–1254","1180–1258":"1180–1258","1247–Female":"1247–Surnud","1250–1308":"1250–1308","1160–1258":"1160–1258","about 1160":"umbes 1160","Abt 1247":"umbes 1247","1250":"1250","August 1258":"august 1258","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","ABT 1250":"umbes 1250","1258":"1258","1247":"1247","1167":"1167","1254":"1254","about 1254":"umbes 1254","1308":"1308","Badenoch, Inverness-Shire, Scotland":"Badenoch, Inverness-shire, Scotland","Buchan, Aberdeen, Scotland":"Buchan, Aberdeenshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Buchan, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Buchan, Aberdeenshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Forres, Morayshire, Scotland":"Forres, Elginshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"about 1160–1258":"noin 1160–1258","1167–1254":"1167–1254","1180–1258":"1180–1258","1247–Female":"1247–Kuollut","1250–1308":"1250–1308","1160–1258":"1160–1258","about 1160":"noin 1160","Abt 1247":"noin 1247","1250":"1250","August 1258":"elokuu 1258","1160":"1160","1180":"1180","ABT 1250":"noin 1250","1258":"1258","1247":"1247","1167":"1167","1254":"1254","about 1254":"noin 1254","1308":"1308","Badeno